entry.content:
Share information
Cube Storage Pioneers

Little Robots, Big Business

Since its inception in 1996, AutoStore™ has worked to improve warehouse efficiency. Today, the company’s key value proposition is to deliver an easy-to-use software powered cubic automatic storage and retrieval ecosystem.

The AutoStore solution is modular and flexible, and can automate any warehouse. The system offers a superior customer value proposition across operating metrics, ESG scores, and customer economics.
‍

View video to learn more

entry.title: Horsham Friends Meeting House (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that the headstone of George Bax Holmes, who is buried at Horsham Friends Meeting House (pictured), is now a paving slab?

entry.title: King Tornado football (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that the King Tornado football team once won by a score of 206–0 – without even playing the full game?

entry.title: Born to Run (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that the album cover for Bruce Springsteen's Born to Run has been imitated by several musicians, as well as the Sesame Street characters Bert and Cookie Monster?

entry.title: Hardpoint (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that as part of the Hardpoint missile defense system, ARPA developed missiles able to hit 377 g of acceleration with reaction times in milliseconds?

entry.title: Enass Muzamel (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Enass Muzamel established the Sudanese Female Cyclists Initiative to challenge the stigma against women riding bikes in Sudan?

entry.title: Milkrun (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that only months after going out of business, Milkrun relaunched?

entry.title: Aaron Hertzman (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Aaron Hertzman paid $25 to have a team in the National Football League?

entry.title: Rubymar (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that Rubymar was the first ship sunk by Houthi missiles during the Red Sea crisis?

entry.title: a Missouri TV station (Wikipedia — did you know?)
entry.content: ... that a Missouri TV station blew up its call letters – literally?
